               <p>567. 
               
                  <persName id="t17940917-109-defend1358" type="defendantName">
                     CHARLES 
                     POLLY
                  <interp inst="t17940917-109-defend1358" type="surname" value="POLLY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17940917-109-defend1358" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17940917-109-defend1358" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
               
             was indicted for <rs id="t17940917-109-off565" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t17940917-109-off565" type="offenceCategory" value="royalOffences"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17940917-109-off565" type="offenceSubcategory" value="coiningOffences"></interp>
               that he, on the <rs id="t17940917-109-cd566" type="crimeDate">3d of September</rs>
                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t17940917-109-off565 t17940917-109-cd566"></join>, a piece of false and counterfeit<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="179409170237"></xptr>money to the likeness of a shilling did utter to 
                     <persName id="t17940917-109-victim1359" type="victimName">
                        Mary 
                        Bedford
                     <interp inst="t17940917-109-victim1359" type="surname" value="Bedford"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t17940917-109-victim1359" type="given" value="Mary"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t17940917-109-victim1359" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t17940917-109-off565 t17940917-109-victim1359"></join>
                     </persName>
                  , spinster, knowing it to be counterfeit
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>(The indictment opened by Mr. - , and the case by Mr. Cullen.)</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17940917-109-person1360">
                  MARY
                   BEDFORD
               <interp inst="t17940917-109-person1360" type="surname" value="BEDFORD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17940917-109-person1360" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17940917-109-person1360" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I am <rs id="t17940917-109-viclabel567" type="occupation">bar maid</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t17940917-109-victim1359 t17940917-109-viclabel567"></join> to Mr. French, at <placeName id="t17940917-109-crimeloc568">the White Horse, in Warwick-lane</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t17940917-109-crimeloc568" type="placeName" value="the White Horse, in Warwick-lane"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t17940917-109-crimeloc568" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t17940917-109-off565 t17940917-109-crimeloc568"></join>; about the 12th of August this person came to me in the bar, between three and four o'clock, as nigh as I can guess; he came and had a glass of Hollands, and he gave me a shilling, and I thought it was a good one, and I put it down and changed it, and he went out; about five minutes after a woman came in and had a glass of shrub, and she gave me a shilling to change, and I looked at it and thought it might be a good one; she said I might give her all half-pence in change.</p>
               <p>Q. Did you see the prisoner again that day? - I did not; my mistress was out.</p>
               <p>Q. What did you do with that shilling that he gave you? - I laid it down very curiously in the till, and I wrapped it up in a bit of paper till she came in. About the 3d of September the prisoner came in again, between three and four or four and five, I cannot positively say, and asked for a glass of Hollands, and he gave me a shilling; it was a plain one; I refused it because I thought it was a bad one, and he gave me another, which was a crooked one, and that I gave change for; I have got it here; I have kept it ever since.</p>
               <p>Q. What did you do with the first shilling? - I gave it him back.</p>
               <p>Q. What happened after that? - The woman came in as usual about five minutes afterwards; my master came out to me about the time the woman came in, and he went after the prisoner immediately.</p>
               <p>Mr. Knapp. On the 3d of September the prisoner gave you a plain one? - He did; I thought it was a bad one.</p>
               <p>Q. And then he gave you this? - Yes.</p>
               <p>Mr. Gullon. What did you do with the money that was tendered to you on the 25th of August? - I have got it here.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17940917-109-person1361">
                  WILLIAM
                   FRENCH
               <interp inst="t17940917-109-person1361" type="surname" value="FRENCH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17940917-109-person1361" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17940917-109-person1361" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I keep a public house in Warwick-lane; on the 3d of September the bar maid gave me a shilling, which had been tendered to her by the prisoner at the bar; she knew that I had ordered this man to be taken into custody the next time he came to the house. I followed him, took him, and charged a constable with him; I see him at the corner of Paternoster-row; there I see him and collared him, and ordered a corman to follow me. I asked him if there was not a lady waiting for him at that house? he said he knew no lady; and when he was brought back they did not know one another at all. I keep the White Horse in Warwick-lane.</p>
               <p>Q. You produce three shillings; where did you get them from? - From the bar maid. We had suspicion of some utterers of bad money using the house, from the vast quantity of bad silver that kept creeping into the till.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17940917-109-person1362">
                  DAVID
                   HUGHES
               <interp inst="t17940917-109-person1362" type="surname" value="HUGHES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17940917-109-person1362" type="given" value="DAVID"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17940917-109-person1362" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I am a constable. I took the prisoner into custody the 3d of September, at the White-house, in Warwick-lane. I searched; I found no bad money on him; he had two or three shillings, some sixpences, and half a crown, a guinea, and some halfpence, I found some bad on the woman, Hannah Burley.</p>

               <p>Mr. Knapp. All the money you found on him was good? - It was, and I returned it again.</p>
               <p>Court to Bedford. Did you see the man and woman in the house together? - Never.</p>
               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="179409170238"></xptr>
            
                  <persName id="t17940917-109-person1363">
                  THOMAS
                   BADER
               <interp inst="t17940917-109-person1363" type="surname" value="BADER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17940917-109-person1363" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17940917-109-person1363" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I was present when Mr. French took the prisoner by the collar; I am servant to Mr. Batterworth, on Holborn-bridge. The prisoner was leaning on the post, by the corner of Paternoster-row; there was another with me. Mr. French comes up and says, I want you two to assist me to take a thief; Ithought he was only joking, but I see him pass by, and seize the prisoner by the collar, and led him towards his own house; and as the prisoner was going, he put his right hand into his right hand breeches pocket, and he threw away a quantity of silver into the kennel. I kept my eye on it, and went to it immediately, and kneeled down, and picked up a shilling, which here it is. One of Mr. French's servants put his hand into the water, and he found two shillings; that shilling I picked up I marked, I can swear to it.</p>
               <p>Mr. Knapp. You always said they were shillings that he threw out of his hands? - It was white, and it appeared to me to be silver.</p>
               <p>Q. Did you say before the justice that the prisoner threw away silver? - I cannot say.</p>
               <p>Q. Why did you say before the magistrate that you see the prisoner throw away something, but what it was you could not tell? - Please your Worship I do not recollect it.</p>
               <p>Court. Whatever he threw away you picked up? - Yes, I did.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17940917-109-person1364">
                  JOHN
                   HALL
               <interp inst="t17940917-109-person1364" type="surname" value="HALL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17940917-109-person1364" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17940917-109-person1364" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I am servant to Mr. French. I found two shillings in the kennel, here they are, I marked them myself.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17940917-109-person1365">
                  WILLIAM
                   PARKER
               <interp inst="t17940917-109-person1365" type="surname" value="PARKER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17940917-109-person1365" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17940917-109-person1365" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>These three shillings are all bad, found in the kennel, and the one shilling he tendered.</p>
               <p>Mr. Knapp. Are you sure of that? - Yes, I am; it is a very good one as a bad one.(Mr. Knapp addressed the jury on the part of the desendant.)</p>
               <p>GEORGE HEMELEY sworn.</p>
               <p>I am a Lieutenant of his Majesty's Navy, on half-pay. I have known the prisoner for six or seven years; I never heard any thing against him in my life.</p>
               <p>Court. What is he? - An artificial flower maker; I have had dealings with him in that line.</p>
               <p>Q. Where do you live? - In Tottenham-court road, Sloane-street. I fell there to the Captains of ships.</p>
               <p>Q. How long since is it that you was in actual service? - In 83, in the Sevile frigate, with Lord George Fitzgerald.</p>
               <p>The prisoner called two other witnesses to his character.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t17940917-109-verdict569" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t17940917-109-verdict569" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t17940917-109-punish570" type="punishmentDescription">
